Absolutely agree.  But apparently, 'octopi' is now acceptable even in authoritative dictionaries (makes me wince too).  It seems that enough people make the same mistake ‚Äì even as in this case it demonstrates appalling ignorance of Latin and Greek ‚Äì  it can become part of the language;  just as meanings change through usage. `Newt' and 'nickname' fall into the category of ignorance which is now perfectly acceptable, albeit for a different reason; while 'decimate' (also makes we wince) and 'nice' (at least it retains two meanings) fall into the latter.  That's the nature of the English language:  having so many speakers spread worldwide, it is bound to be fluid, so we just need to tolerate ignorance as part of the evolutionary process ‚Äì  until the next generation, precious few of whom will have been taught the rudiments of etymology, let alone Greek, Latin, Old English, Old French or old Norse,  give it no further thought.

When someone answers my question of  "How are you?" by "I'm good" I like to retort with "Good to hear that, but I was not enquiring into your state of piety".  And the phrase "My bad" has suddenly caught on too. This ugly construction has been used in the NYT crossword, and I have heard it used by college professors. So it seems to be here to stay.

